{{Coord|43|35|03|N|11|18|57|E|display=title}}
[[File:Tuscany Italy (334557752).jpg|thumb|A characteristic estate in Tuscany]] '''Chiantishire''' is an informal nickname given to an area of [[Tuscany]], Italy, where many [[Upper class English|upper class British citizens]] have moved or usually spend their holidays.<ref name="dict" /> The word is a late 20th century [[neologism]] and derives from [[Chianti]], a red wine produced in central Tuscany, in particular in the provinces of [[Siena]] and [[Florence]].<ref name="wine" /> The location rose to prominence in the UK in the mid 1990s when then Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] chose it as one of his preferred summer retreats.<ref name="blair" /> Celebrities that have owned properties in the area include [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Bryan Ferry]], [[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Richard Gere]].<ref name="celebs" />
The [[Foreign & Commonwealth Office]] estimated in 2012 that there were 28,000 Britons living in Italy.<ref name="aliens" />
==Notes== {{reflist| refs= <ref name="dict">{{cite web | url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/chiantishire | title=Chiantishire | accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> <ref name="wine">{{cite web | url=http://www.flonthego.com/2012/gourmet/11-27/tasting-wine-in-the-chiantishire/ | title=Tasting wine in the Chiantishire | accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> <ref name="blair">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/143464.stm | title=Blair family's Tuscany break | accessdate=18 November 2013 | work=BBC News | date=1 August 1998}}</ref> <ref name="aliens">{{cite web | url=http://www.international-adviser.com/news/europe/spectrum-ifa-targets-chiantishire-market-(1) | title=Spectrum IFA targets the Chiantishire market | accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> <ref name="celebs">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2002/oct/13/buyingpropertyabroad.property | title=Looking for a house in the country? Try Chiantishire | publisher=The Guardian | accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> }}
